\i \cf2 Bagurumba'
\i0   is a folk dance of indigenous \cf4 Bodo tribe\cf2  in \cf4 Assam\cf2  and \cf4 Northeast India\cf2 . It is a traditional dance which is traditionally inherent to one generation to another generations. The Bodo women perform the Bagurumba dance with their colourful 
\i dokhna
\i0 , 
\i jwmgra
\i0  (fasra) and 
\i aronai
\i0 . The Bagurumba dance is accepted as main traditional dance of Bodo people. But there are some other important dances like- \cf5 Bardwisikhla dance\cf2 , \cf5 Mwsaglangnai dance\cf2 , \cf5 Dahal-tungri sibnai dance\cf2 , \cf5 Sikri sikla dance\cf2 , \cf5 Daosri delai dance\cf2 , \cf5 Sa-gwlao mwsanai\cf2 , \cf5 Kopri sibnai mwsanai\cf2  and so on. All these dances are known as Kristi dance. It is also accompanied by musical instruments like kham (a long drum, made of wood and goat skin or other animal\'92s skin), 
\i sifung
\i0  (flute, made of bamboo), jota (made of iron/tama), 
\i serja
\i0  (a bowed instrument, made of wood and animals skin), and gongwna (made of bamboo), 
\i tharkha
\i0  (a piece of split bamboo).\cb1 \
